[[Category:short pages]][[ja:%E9%AB%98%E5%BA%8A%E5%BB%BA%E7%89%A9]][[Category:short pages]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:short pages]][[Category:Raised-floor storehouses]][[Category:short pages]][[Category:properly attributed pages]][[Category:short pages]][[Category:Raised-floor storehouses]][[Category:short pages]][[Category:properly attributed pages]] [[Category:short pages]][[Category:qq]][[Category:short pages]][[Category:Raised-floor storehouses]][[Category:short pages]][[Category:qq]] [[Category:redirect]] [[File:Yoshinogari-iseki takayukashiki-souko.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Reconstructed {{ill|elevated granary|ja|高床倉庫}}, an example of an elevated building, at the [[Yoshinogari site]] in {{ill|Saga Prefecture|ja|佐賀県}}.]]
'''Elevated Building''' (高床建物, *Takayuka-tatemono*) refers to a type of {{ill|architecture|ja|建築物}} where the floor is constructed above ground level, with the underfloor space potentially utilized as part of the living area{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}. It is also called '''elevated architecture''' (高床建築, *Takayuka-kenchiku*). In {{ill|archaeology|ja|考古学}}, it is classified as a type of [[:en:Post_in_ground|post in ground]] building, including archaeological remains such as [[Stilt house|stilt houses]] and {{ill|elevated granary|ja|高床倉庫|elevated granary=elevated granary|lt=elevated granaries}} found at various [[:en:archaeological_site|archaeological sites]]. Structures with floors raised too low to be used as living spaces are distinguished as "raised-floor buildings" (揚床建物, *Ageyuka-tatemono*){{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}.
== Overview ==
Elevated buildings are constructed using {{ill|earthfast posts|ja|掘立柱}} (support pillars) embedded in the ground, with crossbeams called *ōbiki* (大引) or *neda* (根太) laid horizontally to support the floorboards. In Japanese archaeology, the term distinguishes these from [[Pit-house|pit-houses]]—where the floor is dug below ground—and {{ill|ground-level buildings|ja|平地建物}}, which have floors at or slightly above ground level{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|pp=165, 192}}.
Common examples of ancient Japanese elevated structures include {{ill|elevated granary|ja|高床倉庫|elevated granary=elevated granary|lt=elevated granaries}} and [[Stilt house|stilt houses]]{{Sfn|Ishino|2006|pp=10-62}}. However, elevated architecture also encompasses other structures like {{ill|watchtowers|ja|櫓}} and {{ill|shrines|ja|神殿}}. Therefore, archaeologists use the broad term "elevated building" to describe the remains of posthole rows ({{ill|pits (archaeology)|ja|ピット (考古学)}}) believed to represent such structures.<ref>{{Cite web|ja|author=Buried Cultural Properties Center|url=https://www.yoshinogari.jp/ym/episode04/house.html|title=1. Housing and Architecture|work=Yoshinogari Historical Park|accessdate=2022-10-29}}</ref>
Similarly to how terms like "ground-level dwelling" (平地住居) and "pit dwelling" (竪穴住居) have replaced older forms with "式" (*-shiki*), the term "elevated building" (高床建物) has largely supplanted "elevated-style building" (高床式建物) in modern archaeological usage{{Refnest|group=Note|In excavation manuals published by the {{ill|Agency for Cultural Affairs|ja|文化庁}} in the 2010s, these terms are standardized without the "式" suffix{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|pp=117-224}}.}}.
At excavation sites, most remains of posthole buildings are identified through the postholes themselves, while above-ground structures like walls and roofs rarely survive. The depth of postholes tends to correlate with the original pillar height—deeper postholes often indicate elevated buildings (like granaries), while shallower ones suggest raised-floor or ground-level buildings{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}.
After {{ill|World War II|ja|太平洋戦争}}, the discovery of elevated granaries from the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代}} at sites like {{ill|Toro Site|ja|登呂遺跡}} in {{ill|Suruga Ward, Shizuoka|ja|駿河区}} was well-known. It was previously thought that such structures did not exist during the earlier {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代}}. However, in 1977, posthole rows indicating an elevated building were discovered at the {{ill|Agu Site|ja|阿久遺跡}} in {{ill|Hara Village, Nagano|ja|原村}}, dating to the Early Jōmon. Initially misidentified as "rectangular pit groups," they were only recognized as building remains after the 1988 discovery of structural elements with through-holes at the {{ill|Sakuramachi Site|ja|桜町遺跡}} in {{ill|Oyabe, Toyama|ja|小矢部市}}, confirming the presence of elevated buildings from the Early Jōmon{{Sfn|Ishino|2006|pp=187-189}}.
== Structure ==
[[File:Ikegami-sone ruins04s3200.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Reconstructed elevated building with a "roof granary" design at the {{ill|Ikegami-Sone Site|ja|池上・曽根遺跡}} in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府}}.]]
Elevated buildings are believed to have existed in two main forms: structures with walls above the floor and those without walls, where the roof (often gabled) covers the floor directly—a design known as a "roof granary" (屋根倉, *yanegura*){{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}. Elevated granaries at sites like {{ill|Toro Site|ja|登呂遺跡}} and {{ill|Yamaki Site|ja|山木遺跡}} in {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県}} are reconstructed in the former style, while large posthole buildings at the {{ill|Ikegami-Sone Site|ja|池上・曽根遺跡}} in {{ill|Izumi|ja|和泉市}} and {{ill|Izumiotsu|ja|泉大津市}}, {{ill|Osaka|ja|大阪府}}, are reconstructed as roof granaries{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}.
