'''Raised-floor buildings''' (高床建物, *Takayuka-tatemono*) are a type of {{ill|architecture|ja|建築物|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} where the floor is constructed above ground level, with the space beneath the floor sometimes used as part of the living area. They are also known as '''raised-floor architecture''' (高床建築, *Takayuka-kenchiku*). In {{ill|archaeology|ja|考古学|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, they are classified as a subtype of [[:en:Post_in_ground|Post in ground buildings]], and structures identified as {{ill|Stilt house|ja|高床住居|lt=Stilt houses|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} or {{ill|raised-floor warehouses|ja|高床倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
 from archaeological sites fall under this category. Structures with floors slightly elevated but not usable as living space are distinguished as "lifted-floor buildings" (揚床建物, *Ageyuka-tatemono*).

== Overview ==

Raised-floor buildings are constructed by placing horizontal beams, known as *Ōbiki* and *Neda*, on top of vertical {{ill|postholes|ja|掘立柱|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (support posts), with planks laid over them to form the floor above ground level. In Japanese archaeology, this term distinguishes them from {{ill|pit-house|ja|竪穴建物|lt=pit-houses|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which have floors dug below ground level, and from {{ill|ground-level buildings|ja|平地建物|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where the floor is at or slightly above ground level.

While {{ill|raised-floor warehouses|ja|高床倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
 and {{ill|raised-floor dwellings|ja|高床住居|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} are well-known examples of ancient Japanese raised-floor structures, other forms like {{ill|watchtowers|ja|櫓|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|shrines|ja|神殿|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} are also assumed to have existed. Therefore, the term "raised-floor buildings" is now used comprehensively in archaeology to refer to posthole structures presumed to have been raised-floor constructions.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|author={{ill|Buried Cultural Properties Center|ja|埋蔵文化財センター|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}|url=https://www.yoshinogari.jp/ym/episode04/house.html|title=1. Housing and Architecture|website={{ill|Yoshinogari Historical Park|ja|国営吉野ヶ里歴史公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}|access-date=2022-10-29}}</ref>

Similar to the shift from using "style" (式) in terms like "ground-level style dwellings" to simply "ground-level dwellings," the usage of "style" in "raised-floor style buildings" (高床式建物) has declined.{{Refnest|group=Note|In excavation manuals published by the {{ill|Agency for Cultural Affairs|ja|文化庁|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} since the 2010s, the term "style" has been omitted from these designations.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|pp=117–224}}}}

In actual {{ill|excavation|ja|発掘調査|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} contexts, most posthole building remains are identified only by posthole traces, with walls, roofs, or above-ground structures rarely preserved. However, the depth of postholes tends to correspond to the height of the original posts, with deeper postholes suggesting raised-floor buildings (like warehouses) and shallower ones indicating lifted-floor or ground-level structures.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}

In post-{{ill|World War II|ja|太平洋戦争|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Japanese archaeological history, raised-floor structures were known from {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} sites like the {{ill|Toro site|ja|登呂遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Shizuoka City|ja|静岡市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, but were thought absent in the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, in 1977, posthole alignments suggesting raised-floor buildings were discovered at the {{ill|Agu site|ja|阿久遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Hara Village|ja|原村|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, though initially identified as "rectangular pit groups." In 1988, excavations at the {{ill|Sakuramachi site|ja|桜町遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Oyabe City|ja|小矢部市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Toyama Prefecture|ja|富山県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, uncovered post materials with mortise holes, confirming that raised-floor buildings existed as early as the Early Jōmon period.{{Sfn|Ishino|2006|pp=187–189}}

== Forms ==

[[File:Ikegami-sone ruins04s3200.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Reconstruction of a raised-floor building in the "roof-storehouse" style at the [[Ikegami-Sone Site]] in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.]]

Raised-floor buildings are thought to have existed in two forms: one with walls above the floor, and another called "roof-storehouses" (屋根倉, *Yanegura*), where the roof (usually {{ill|gabled|ja|切妻屋根|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) rests directly on the floor without walls.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}} The typical {{ill|raised-floor warehouse|ja|高床倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
 is reconstructed with walls, based on findings from sites like the {{ill|Toro site|ja|登呂遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Yamaki site|ja|山木遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Roof-storehouse style reconstructions can be seen in large posthole buildings at the {{ill|Ikegami-Sone Site|ja|池上・曽根遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} spanning {{ill|Izumi|ja|和泉市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Izumiotsu|ja|泉大津市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}

