'''Raised-floor buildings''' (高床建物, *Takayuka-tatemono*) are a type of [[:en:Building|architecture]] where the floor is constructed above ground level, with the space beneath the floor sometimes used as part of the living area. They are also known as '''raised-floor architecture''' (高床建築, *Takayuka-kenchiku*). In [[:en:Archaeology|archaeology]], they are classified as a subtype of [[:en:Post_in_ground|Post in ground buildings]], and structures identified as {{ill|Stilt house|ja|高床住居|lt=Stilt houses|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Stilt house|qq=}} or {{ill|raised-floor warehouses|ja|高床倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/raised-floor warehouses|13=User:Immanuelle/Raised-floor warehouse|qq=}}
 from archaeological sites fall under this category. Structures with floors slightly elevated but not usable as living space are distinguished as "lifted-floor buildings" (揚床建物, *Ageyuka-tatemono*).

== Overview ==

Raised-floor buildings are constructed by placing horizontal beams, known as *Ōbiki* and *Neda*, on top of vertical {{ill|postholes|ja|掘立柱|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/postholes|qq=}} (support posts), with planks laid over them to form the floor above ground level. In Japanese archaeology, this term distinguishes them from {{ill|pit-house|ja|竪穴建物|lt=pit-houses|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pit-house|qq=}}, which have floors dug below ground level, and from {{ill|ground-level buildings|ja|平地建物|1=Flatland dwellings|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ground-level buildings|qq=}}, where the floor is at or slightly above ground level.

While {{ill|raised-floor warehouses|ja|高床倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/raised-floor warehouses|13=User:Immanuelle/Raised-floor warehouse|qq=}}
 and {{ill|raised-floor dwellings|ja|高床住居|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/raised-floor dwellings|qq=}} are well-known examples of ancient Japanese raised-floor structures, other forms like {{ill|watchtowers|ja|櫓|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/watchtowers|qq=}} and [[:en:Temple|shrines]] are also assumed to have existed. Therefore, the term "raised-floor buildings" is now used comprehensively in archaeology to refer to posthole structures presumed to have been raised-floor constructions.<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|author={{ill|Buried Cultural Properties Center|ja|埋蔵文化財センター|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buried Cultural Properties Center|qq=}}|url=https://www.yoshinogari.jp/ym/episode04/house.html|title=1. Housing and Architecture|website={{ill|Yoshinogari Historical Park|ja|国営吉野ヶ里歴史公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshinogari Historical Park|qq=}}|access-date=2022-10-29}}</ref>

Similar to the shift from using "style" (式) in terms like "ground-level style dwellings" to simply "ground-level dwellings," the usage of "style" in "raised-floor style buildings" (高床式建物) has declined.{{Refnest|group=Note|In excavation manuals published by the [[:en:Agency for Cultural Affairs|Agency for Cultural Affairs]] since the 2010s, the term "style" has been omitted from these designations.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|pp=117–224}}}}

In actual [[:en:Archaeological excavation|excavation]] contexts, most posthole building remains are identified only by posthole traces, with walls, roofs, or above-ground structures rarely preserved. However, the depth of postholes tends to correspond to the height of the original posts, with deeper postholes suggesting raised-floor buildings (like warehouses) and shallower ones indicating lifted-floor or ground-level structures.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}

In post-[[:en:Pacific War|World War II]] Japanese archaeological history, raised-floor structures were known from [[:en:Yayoi period|Yayoi period]] sites like the [[:en:Toro (archaeological site)|Toro site]] in [[:en:Shizuoka (city)|Shizuoka City]], but were thought absent in the [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]]. However, in 1977, posthole alignments suggesting raised-floor buildings were discovered at the [[:en:Akyū ruins|Agu site]] in [[:en:Hara, Nagano|Hara Village]], [[:en:Nagano Prefecture|Nagano Prefecture]], though initially identified as "rectangular pit groups." In 1988, excavations at the {{ill|Sakuramachi site|ja|桜町遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakuramachi site|qq=}} in [[:en:Oyabe, Toyama|Oyabe City]], [[:en:Toyama Prefecture|Toyama Prefecture]], uncovered post materials with mortise holes, confirming that raised-floor buildings existed as early as the Early Jōmon period.{{Sfn|Ishino|2006|pp=187–189}}

