Raised-floor buildings are thought to have existed in two forms: one with walls above the floor, and another called "roof-storehouses" (屋根倉, *Yanegura*), where the roof (usually [[:en:Gable roof|gabled]]) rests directly on the floor without walls.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}} The typical {{ill|raised-floor warehouse|ja|高床式倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|2=ja|3=高床式倉庫|1=Raised-floor warehouse|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/raised-floor warehouse|13=User:Immanuelle/Raised-floor warehouse|qq=}} is reconstructed with walls, based on findings from sites like the [[:en:Toro (archaeological site)|Toro site]] and {{ill|Yamaki site|ja|山木遺跡|qq=|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaki site}} in [[:en:Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka Prefecture]]. Roof-storehouse style reconstructions can be seen in large posthole buildings at the [[:en:Ikegami-Sone Site|Ikegami-Sone Site]] spanning [[:en:Izumi, Osaka|Izumi]] and [[:en:Izumiōtsu|Izumiotsu]] in [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]].{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Monuments Division|2013|p=165}}
